{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780736002680,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_dy4wf9vezily_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: State Format Reference\n3: description: Live state packet hub for the deep-research loop.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # State Format Reference\n7: \n8: Live state packet hub for deep-research files, mutability, and routed state references.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### Purpose\n15: \n16: Summarize the live deep-research packet files, mutability rules, and focused state references without carrying every JSON shape inline.\n17: \n18: ### When to Use\n19: \n20: Load this hub when navigating packet files, deciding file ownership, or choosing which detailed state reference to load next.\n21: \n22: ### Routed Details\n23: \n24: - `state_jsonl.md` for config, iteration, event, lifecycle, graph, and blocked-stop records.\n25: - `state_outputs.md` for strategy, iteration markdown, `research.md`, dashboard, and resource-map output.\n26: - `state_reducer_registry.md` for reducer ownership, findings registry, validation, reconstruction, and file protection.\n27: \n28: For iterative code review state, use `deep-review`. Review-mode state is not part of this skill's live state contract.\n29: \n30: ### Packet Summary\n31: \n32: The deep-research loop persists continuity in packet files so each iteration can run with fresh context.\n33: \n34: | File | Format | Purpose | Mutability |\n35: |------|--------|---------|------------|\n36: | `deep-research-config.json` | JSON | Loop parameters and lineage | Created at init; read-only after |\n37: | `deep-research-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Append-only structured log | Append-only |\n38: | `deep-research-strategy.md` | Markdown | Current research plan and next focus | Reducer-managed sections |\n39: | `deep-research-findings-registry.json` / `findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned findings and question state | Auto-generated |\n40: | `deep-research-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Operator summary | Auto-generated |\n41: | `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration narrative | Write-once |\n42: | `deltas/iter-NNN.jsonl` | JSONL | Per-iteration structured delta | Write-once |\n43: | `research.md` | Markdown | Final/progressive synthesis | Workflow-owned |\n44: | `resource-map.md` | Markdown | Optional evidence-derived resource map | Workflow-owned |\n45: \n46: The artifact directory is resolved by `resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'research')` from `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs`.\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 2. PACKET LOCATION\n51: \n52: Root specs use:\n53: \n54: ```text\n55: {spec_folder}/research/\n56: ```\n57: \n58: Child-phase and sub-phase targets use flat-first behavior:\n59: \n60: - first run with an empty local `research/` directory writes flat at `{spec_folder}/research/`;\n61: - a `{basename(spec_folder)}-pt-NN` subfolder is allocated only when prior content already exists for a non-matching target;\n62: - continuation runs reuse the existing matching packet.\n63: \n64: This avoids an unnecessary `pt-01` wrapper on first runs.\n65: \n66: ---\n67: \n68: ## 3. OWNERSHIP MODEL\n69: \n70: | Owner | Writes |\n71: |-------|--------|\n72: | Agent iteration | `iterations/iteration-NNN.md`, JSONL iteration/event append, optional progressive synthesis contribution |\n73: | Workflow reducer | strategy machine-owned sections, findings registry, dashboard |\n74: | Workflow synthesis | `research.md`, lifecycle snapshots |\n75: | Spec anchoring protocol | bounded `spec.md` seed/context/fenced findings block |\n76: \n77: The reducer is the source of truth for derived state. Manual edits to reducer-owned outputs are overwritten on the next refresh.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 4. FILE PROTECTION\n82: \n83: | Protection | Meaning |\n84: |------------|---------|\n85: | `immutable` | Created once and not modified after init |\n86: | `append-only` | New JSONL records may be appended; existing records are not rewritten |\n87: | `write-once` | Each iteration artifact is created once |\n88: | `mutable` | Workflow may update the file under defined ownership rules |\n89: | `auto-generated` | Reducer/workflow regenerates the full file |\n90: \n91: The config file carries the protection map; details live in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n92: \n93: ---\n94: \n95: ## 5. ROUTED REFERENCES\n96: \n97: | Resource | Use When |\n98: |----------|----------|\n99: | `state_jsonl.md` | Need the JSONL config, iteration, event, lineage, graph, or blocked-stop schemas |\n100: | `state_outputs.md` | Need markdown output structure for strategy, iterations, dashboard, research synthesis, or resource map |\n101: | `state_reducer_registry.md` | Need reducer ownership, registry schema, validation, fault tolerance, or reconstruction |\n102: | `../convergence/convergence.md` | Need STOP contract and legal-stop semantics |\n103: | `../protocol/spec_check_protocol.md` | Need bounded `spec.md` anchoring and generated-fence write-back |\n104: \n105: ---\n106: \n107: ## 6. NON-GOALS\n108: \n109: - Do not document `deep-review` state here; route to the sibling skill.\n110: - Do not treat legacy aliases as write targets. The workflow reads legacy aliases only for migration windows and writes canonical `deep-research-*` names.\n111: - Do not manually edit reducer-owned dashboard or registry files.\n\n(End of file - total 111 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: State Format Reference\ndescription: Live state packet hub for the deep-research loop.\n---\n\n# State Format Reference\n\nLive state packet hub for deep-research files, mutability, and routed state references.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nSummarize the live deep-research packet files, mutability rules, and focused state references without carrying every JSON shape inline.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this hub when navigating packet files, deciding file ownership, or choosing which detailed state reference to load next.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md","text":"---\ntitle: State Format Reference\ndescription: Live state packet hub for the deep-research loop.\n---\n\n# State Format Reference\n\nLive state packet hub for deep-research files, mutability, and routed state references.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nSummarize the live deep-research packet files, mutability rules, and focused state references without carrying every JSON shape inline.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this hub when navigating packet files, deciding file ownership, or choosing which detailed state reference to load next.\n\n### Routed Details\n\n- `state_jsonl.md` for config, iteration, event, lifecycle, graph, and blocked-stop records.\n- `state_outputs.md` for strategy, iteration markdown, `research.md`, dashboard, and resource-map output.\n- `state_reducer_registry.md` for reducer ownership, findings registry, validation, reconstruction, and file protection.\n\nFor iterative code review state, use `deep-review`. Review-mode state is not part of this skill's live state contract.\n\n### Packet Summary\n\nThe deep-research loop persists continuity in packet files so each iteration can run with fresh context.\n\n| File | Format | Purpose | Mutability |\n|------|--------|---------|------------|\n| `deep-research-config.json` | JSON | Loop parameters and lineage | Created at init; read-only after |\n| `deep-research-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Append-only structured log | Append-only |\n| `deep-research-strategy.md` | Markdown | Current research plan and next focus | Reducer-managed sections |\n| `deep-research-findings-registry.json` / `findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned findings and question state | Auto-generated |\n| `deep-research-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Operator summary | Auto-generated |\n| `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration narrative | Write-once |\n| `deltas/iter-NNN.jsonl` | JSONL | Per-iteration structured delta | Write-once |\n| `research.md` | Markdown | Final/progressive synthesis | Workflow-owned |\n| `resource-map.md` | Markdown | Optional evidence-derived resource map | Workflow-owned |\n\nThe artifact directory is resolved by `resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'research')` from `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. PACKET LOCATION\n\nRoot specs use:\n\n```text\n{spec_folder}/research/\n```\n\nChild-phase and sub-phase targets use flat-first behavior:\n\n- first run with an empty local `research/` directory writes flat at `{spec_folder}/research/`;\n- a `{basename(spec_folder)}-pt-NN` subfolder is allocated only when prior content already exists for a non-matching target;\n- continuation runs reuse the existing matching packet.\n\nThis avoids an unnecessary `pt-01` wrapper on first runs.\n\n---\n\n## 3. OWNERSHIP MODEL\n\n| Owner | Writes |\n|-------|--------|\n| Agent iteration | `iterations/iteration-NNN.md`, JSONL iteration/event append, optional progressive synthesis contribution |\n| Workflow reducer | strategy machine-owned sections, findings registry, dashboard |\n| Workflow synthesis | `research.md`, lifecycle snapshots |\n| Spec anchoring protocol | bounded `spec.md` seed/context/fenced findings block |\n\nThe reducer is the source of truth for derived state. Manual edits to reducer-owned outputs are overwritten on the next refresh.\n\n---\n\n## 4. FILE PROTECTION\n\n| Protection | Meaning |\n|------------|---------|\n| `immutable` | Created once and not modified after init |\n| `append-only` | New JSONL records may be appended; existing records are not rewritten |\n| `write-once` | Each iteration artifact is created once |\n| `mutable` | Workflow may update the file under defined ownership rules |\n| `auto-generated` | Reducer/workflow regenerates the full file |\n\nThe config file carries the protection map; details live in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. ROUTED REFERENCES\n\n| Resource | Use When |\n|----------|----------|\n| `state_jsonl.md` | Need the JSONL config, iteration, event, lineage, graph, or blocked-stop schemas |\n| `state_outputs.md` | Need markdown output structure for strategy, iterations, dashboard, research synthesis, or resource map |\n| `state_reducer_registry.md` | Need reducer ownership, registry schema, validation, fault tolerance, or reconstruction |\n| `../convergence/convergence.md` | Need STOP contract and legal-stop semantics |\n| `../protocol/spec_check_protocol.md` | Need bounded `spec.md` anchoring and generated-fence write-back |\n\n---\n\n## 6. NON-GOALS\n\n- Do not document `deep-review` state here; route to the sibling skill.\n- Do not treat legacy aliases as write targets. The workflow reads legacy aliases only for migration windows and writes canonical `deep-research-*` names.\n- Do not manually edit reducer-owned dashboard or registry files.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":111,"totalLines":111,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md","time":{"start":1780736002667,"end":1780736002678}},"id":"prt_e9c230485001wu42hZkplOq0Na","sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","messageID":"msg_e9c22f4e7001AVFbL8QlqZeuBd"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780736003936,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_dy4wf9vezily_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_jsonl.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_jsonl.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Research JSONL State Reference\n3: description: Config, iteration, event, lineage, graph, and blocked-stop records for deep-research state logs.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Deep Research JSONL State Reference\n7: \n8: `deep-research-state.jsonl` is append-only. Each line is one JSON object. The first line is normally the config record, followed by iteration and event records.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### Purpose\n15: \n16: Define the append-only JSONL records used by deep-research config, iteration, lifecycle, graph, pause, stuck-recovery, and blocked-stop state.\n17: \n18: ### When to Use\n19: \n20: Load this reference when validating state logs, adding event records, reconstructing a packet, or mapping legacy stop labels to current values.\n21: \n22: ### Core Principle\n23: \n24: Raw JSONL is append-only evidence. Reducer-owned files derive from it, but they do not replace it.\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## 2. CONFIG RECORD\n29: \n30: The config record captures the initialized loop contract.\n31: \n32: ```json\n33: {\n34:   \"type\": \"config\",\n35:   \"topic\": \"API response time optimization\",\n36:   \"maxIterations\": 10,\n37:   \"convergenceThreshold\": 0.05,\n38:   \"stuckThreshold\": 3,\n39:   \"specFolder\": \"028-auto-deep-research\",\n40:   \"createdAt\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n41: }\n42: ```\n43: \n44: The full config file also stores executor, lineage, reducer, capability matrix, pause sentinel, archive, and file-protection settings.\n45: \n46: ---\n47: \n48: ## 3. ITERATION RECORDS\n49: \n50: ```json\n51: {\n52:   \"type\": \"iteration\",\n53:   \"run\": 1,\n54:   \"status\": \"complete\",\n55:   \"focus\": \"Initial broad survey\",\n56:   \"findingsCount\": 5,\n57:   \"newInfoRatio\": 1.0,\n58:   \"noveltyJustification\": \"First pass; all findings are new to this packet\",\n59:   \"keyQuestions\": [\"What causes latency?\"],\n60:   \"answeredQuestions\": [\"What causes latency?\"],\n61:   \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:05:00Z\",\n62:   \"durationMs\": 45000\n63: }\n64: ```\n65: \n66: | Field | Required | Notes |\n67: |-------|----------|-------|\n68: | `type` | Yes | `iteration` |\n69: | `run` | Yes | 1-indexed iteration number |\n70: | `status` | Yes | See status values below |\n71: | `focus` | Yes | Single focus investigated |\n72: | `findingsCount` | Yes | Number of findings reported |\n73: | `newInfoRatio` | Yes | Novelty score used by convergence |\n74: | `noveltyJustification` | Recommended | One-sentence explanation of the ratio |\n75: | `keyQuestions` | Recommended | Questions considered during this iteration |\n76: | `answeredQuestions` | Recommended | Questions answered by evidence |\n77: | `ruledOut` | Optional | Negative knowledge entries |\n78: | `graphEvents` | Optional | Coverage graph mutations |\n79: \n80: Status values:\n81: \n82: | Status | Meaning |\n83: |--------|---------|\n84: | `complete` | Normal evidence-gathering iteration |\n85: | `timeout` | Time/tool budget exceeded |\n86: | `error` | Tool, parse, or unexpected failure |\n87: | `stuck` | No new information and no clear next direction |\n88: | `insight` | Low ratio but important conceptual breakthrough |\n89: | `thought` | Analytical-only iteration; excluded from stuck and signal math |\n90: \n91: ---\n92: \n93: ## 4. CONVERGENCE SIGNAL FIELDS\n94: \n95: When the composite algorithm runs, the iteration may include signal values:\n96: \n97: ```json\n98: {\n99:   \"type\": \"iteration\",\n100:   \"run\": 5,\n101:   \"convergenceSignals\": {\n102:     \"rollingAvg\": 0.12,\n103:     \"madScore\": 0.08,\n104:     \"entropyCoverage\": 0.71,\n105:     \"compositeStop\": 0.42\n106:   }\n107: }\n108: ```\n109: \n110: Signal rules live in `../convergence/convergence_signals.md`.\n111: \n112: ---\n113: \n114: ## 5. NEGATIVE KNOWLEDGE\n115: \n116: Use `ruledOut` to preserve eliminated approaches.\n117: \n118: ```json\n119: {\n120:   \"type\": \"iteration\",\n121:   \"run\": 3,\n122:   \"status\": \"complete\",\n123:   \"ruledOut\": [\n124:     {\n125:       \"approach\": \"HTTP/3 multiplexing\",\n126:       \"reason\": \"No server-side support in target environment\",\n127:       \"evidence\": \"file:docs/protocols.md:42\"\n128:     }\n129:   ]\n130: }\n131: ```\n132: \n133: Ruled-out directions should also appear in strategy and synthesis outputs.\n134: \n135: ---\n136: \n137: ## 6. GRAPH EVENTS\n138: \n139: `graphEvents` records coverage graph mutations from an iteration.\n140: \n141: ```json\n142: {\n143:   \"type\": \"iteration\",\n144:   \"run\": 4,\n145:   \"graphEvents\": [\n146:     {\"type\": \"question\", \"id\": \"q-reconnect\", \"label\": \"How should reconnect work?\"},\n147:     {\"type\": \"finding\", \"id\": \"f-backoff\", \"label\": \"Exponential backoff is required\"},\n148:     {\"type\": \"edge\", \"from\": \"f-backoff\", \"to\": \"q-reconnect\", \"relation\": \"ANSWERS\"}\n149:   ]\n150: }\n151: ```\n152: \n153: Valid node types are `question`, `finding`, `claim`, and `source`; `edge` records connect nodes. IDs must be unique within a single `(specFolder, loopType, sessionId)` namespace. Reusing the same logical ID across independent sessions is allowed because the coverage graph uses a composite key.\n154: \n155: ---\n156: \n157: ## 7. EVENT RECORDS\n158: \n159: Lifecycle event:\n160: \n161: ```json\n162: {\n163:   \"type\": \"event\",\n164:   \"event\": \"resumed\",\n165:   \"mode\": \"research\",\n166:   \"sessionId\": \"dr-2026-05-24T00-00-00Z\",\n167:   \"parentSessionId\": \"dr-2026-05-24T00-00-00Z\",\n168:   \"lineageMode\": \"resume\",\n169:   \"continuedFromRun\": 4,\n170:   \"generation\": 1,\n171:   \"archivedPath\": null,\n172:   \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n173: }\n174: ```\n175: \n176: Blocked stop event:\n177: \n178: ```json\n179: {\n180:   \"type\": \"event\",\n181:   \"event\": \"blocked_stop\",\n182:   \"mode\": \"research\",\n183:   \"run\": 7,\n184:   \"stopReason\": \"blockedStop\",\n185:   \"blockedBy\": [\"keyQuestionCoverage\", \"sourceDiversity\"],\n186:   \"recoveryStrategy\": \"focus_pivot\",\n187:   \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n188: }\n189: ```\n190: \n191: Pause event:\n192: \n193: ```json\n194: {\n195:   \"type\": \"event\",\n196:   \"event\": \"userPaused\",\n197:   \"mode\": \"research\",\n198:   \"run\": 7,\n199:   \"stopReason\": \"userPaused\",\n200:   \"sentinelPath\": \"research/.deep-research-pause\",\n201:   \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n202: }\n203: ```\n204: \n205: Stuck recovery event:\n206: \n207: ```json\n208: {\n209:   \"type\": \"event\",\n210:   \"event\": \"stuckRecovery\",\n211:   \"mode\": \"research\",\n212:   \"run\": 7,\n213:   \"stopReason\": \"stuckRecovery\",\n214:   \"fromFocus\": \"Connection pooling\",\n215:   \"toFocus\": \"Transport alternatives\",\n216:   \"strategy\": \"try_opposites\",\n217:   \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n218: }\n219: ```\n220: \n221: Graph convergence event shape lives in `../convergence/convergence_graph.md`.\n222: \n223: ---\n224: \n225: ## 8. NORMALIZATION\n226: \n227: Emission-time normalization maps legacy labels into canonical `stopReason` values before persistence. The mapping lives in `../convergence/convergence.md`.\n228: \n229: Malformed lines are handled by the reducer according to its strict/lenient mode. Fault tolerance and reconstruction are documented in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n\n(End of file - total 229 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Research JSONL State Reference\ndescription: Config, iteration, event, lineage, graph, and blocked-stop records for deep-research state logs.\n---\n\n# Deep Research JSONL State Reference\n\n`deep-research-state.jsonl` is append-only. Each line is one JSON object. The first line is normally the config record, followed by iteration and event records.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefine the append-only JSONL records used by deep-research config, iteration, lifecycle, graph, pause, stuck-recovery, and blocked-stop state.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this reference when validating state logs, adding event records, reconstructing a packet, or mapping legacy stop labels to current values.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_jsonl.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Research JSONL State Reference\ndescription: Config, iteration, event, lineage, graph, and blocked-stop records for deep-research state logs.\n---\n\n# Deep Research JSONL State Reference\n\n`deep-research-state.jsonl` is append-only. Each line is one JSON object. The first line is normally the config record, followed by iteration and event records.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefine the append-only JSONL records used by deep-research config, iteration, lifecycle, graph, pause, stuck-recovery, and blocked-stop state.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this reference when validating state logs, adding event records, reconstructing a packet, or mapping legacy stop labels to current values.\n\n### Core Principle\n\nRaw JSONL is append-only evidence. Reducer-owned files derive from it, but they do not replace it.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CONFIG RECORD\n\nThe config record captures the initialized loop contract.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"config\",\n  \"topic\": \"API response time optimization\",\n  \"maxIterations\": 10,\n  \"convergenceThreshold\": 0.05,\n  \"stuckThreshold\": 3,\n  \"specFolder\": \"028-auto-deep-research\",\n  \"createdAt\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n}\n```\n\nThe full config file also stores executor, lineage, reducer, capability matrix, pause sentinel, archive, and file-protection settings.\n\n---\n\n## 3. ITERATION RECORDS\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"iteration\",\n  \"run\": 1,\n  \"status\": \"complete\",\n  \"focus\": \"Initial broad survey\",\n  \"findingsCount\": 5,\n  \"newInfoRatio\": 1.0,\n  \"noveltyJustification\": \"First pass; all findings are new to this packet\",\n  \"keyQuestions\": [\"What causes latency?\"],\n  \"answeredQuestions\": [\"What causes latency?\"],\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:05:00Z\",\n  \"durationMs\": 45000\n}\n```\n\n| Field | Required | Notes |\n|-------|----------|-------|\n| `type` | Yes | `iteration` |\n| `run` | Yes | 1-indexed iteration number |\n| `status` | Yes | See status values below |\n| `focus` | Yes | Single focus investigated |\n| `findingsCount` | Yes | Number of findings reported |\n| `newInfoRatio` | Yes | Novelty score used by convergence |\n| `noveltyJustification` | Recommended | One-sentence explanation of the ratio |\n| `keyQuestions` | Recommended | Questions considered during this iteration |\n| `answeredQuestions` | Recommended | Questions answered by evidence |\n| `ruledOut` | Optional | Negative knowledge entries |\n| `graphEvents` | Optional | Coverage graph mutations |\n\nStatus values:\n\n| Status | Meaning |\n|--------|---------|\n| `complete` | Normal evidence-gathering iteration |\n| `timeout` | Time/tool budget exceeded |\n| `error` | Tool, parse, or unexpected failure |\n| `stuck` | No new information and no clear next direction |\n| `insight` | Low ratio but important conceptual breakthrough |\n| `thought` | Analytical-only iteration; excluded from stuck and signal math |\n\n---\n\n## 4. CONVERGENCE SIGNAL FIELDS\n\nWhen the composite algorithm runs, the iteration may include signal values:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"iteration\",\n  \"run\": 5,\n  \"convergenceSignals\": {\n    \"rollingAvg\": 0.12,\n    \"madScore\": 0.08,\n    \"entropyCoverage\": 0.71,\n    \"compositeStop\": 0.42\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSignal rules live in `../convergence/convergence_signals.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. NEGATIVE KNOWLEDGE\n\nUse `ruledOut` to preserve eliminated approaches.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"iteration\",\n  \"run\": 3,\n  \"status\": \"complete\",\n  \"ruledOut\": [\n    {\n      \"approach\": \"HTTP/3 multiplexing\",\n      \"reason\": \"No server-side support in target environment\",\n      \"evidence\": \"file:docs/protocols.md:42\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nRuled-out directions should also appear in strategy and synthesis outputs.\n\n---\n\n## 6. GRAPH EVENTS\n\n`graphEvents` records coverage graph mutations from an iteration.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"iteration\",\n  \"run\": 4,\n  \"graphEvents\": [\n    {\"type\": \"question\", \"id\": \"q-reconnect\", \"label\": \"How should reconnect work?\"},\n    {\"type\": \"finding\", \"id\": \"f-backoff\", \"label\": \"Exponential backoff is required\"},\n    {\"type\": \"edge\", \"from\": \"f-backoff\", \"to\": \"q-reconnect\", \"relation\": \"ANSWERS\"}\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nValid node types are `question`, `finding`, `claim`, and `source`; `edge` records connect nodes. IDs must be unique within a single `(specFolder, loopType, sessionId)` namespace. Reusing the same logical ID across independent sessions is allowed because the coverage graph uses a composite key.\n\n---\n\n## 7. EVENT RECORDS\n\nLifecycle event:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"resumed\",\n  \"mode\": \"research\",\n  \"sessionId\": \"dr-2026-05-24T00-00-00Z\",\n  \"parentSessionId\": \"dr-2026-05-24T00-00-00Z\",\n  \"lineageMode\": \"resume\",\n  \"continuedFromRun\": 4,\n  \"generation\": 1,\n  \"archivedPath\": null,\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n}\n```\n\nBlocked stop event:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"blocked_stop\",\n  \"mode\": \"research\",\n  \"run\": 7,\n  \"stopReason\": \"blockedStop\",\n  \"blockedBy\": [\"keyQuestionCoverage\", \"sourceDiversity\"],\n  \"recoveryStrategy\": \"focus_pivot\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n}\n```\n\nPause event:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"userPaused\",\n  \"mode\": \"research\",\n  \"run\": 7,\n  \"stopReason\": \"userPaused\",\n  \"sentinelPath\": \"research/.deep-research-pause\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n}\n```\n\nStuck recovery event:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"stuckRecovery\",\n  \"mode\": \"research\",\n  \"run\": 7,\n  \"stopReason\": \"stuckRecovery\",\n  \"fromFocus\": \"Connection pooling\",\n  \"toFocus\": \"Transport alternatives\",\n  \"strategy\": \"try_opposites\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\"\n}\n```\n\nGraph convergence event shape lives in `../convergence/convergence_graph.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. NORMALIZATION\n\nEmission-time normalization maps legacy labels into canonical `stopReason` values before persistence. The mapping lives in `../convergence/convergence.md`.\n\nMalformed lines are handled by the reducer according to its strict/lenient mode. Fault tolerance and reconstruction are documented in `state_reducer_registry.md`.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":229,"totalLines":229,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_jsonl.md","time":{"start":1780736003921,"end":1780736003933}},"id":"prt_e9c230a70001pwJaRvv5LBXR2z","sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","messageID":"msg_e9c22f4e7001AVFbL8QlqZeuBd"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780736003947,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_dy4wf9vezily_3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_outputs.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_outputs.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Research Output Files Reference\n3: description: Markdown output structures for strategy, iterations, dashboard, synthesis, and resource-map artifacts.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Deep Research Output Files Reference\n7: \n8: This reference covers human-readable packet outputs. JSONL records live in `state_jsonl.md`; reducer ownership lives in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### Purpose\n15: \n16: Define the human-readable deep-research packet outputs: strategy, iteration markdown, synthesis, dashboard, resource map, and bounded spec anchoring.\n17: \n18: ### When to Use\n19: \n20: Load this reference when writing or validating markdown outputs rather than JSONL records.\n21: \n22: ### Core Principle\n23: \n24: Human-readable outputs must stay synchronized with raw state and respect reducer ownership.\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## 2. STRATEGY FILE\n29: \n30: `deep-research-strategy.md` is the persistent research plan. The reducer owns machine-managed sections.\n31: \n32: Required sections:\n33: \n34: - Research Topic\n35: - Known Context\n36: - Key Questions\n37: - Answered Questions\n38: - What Worked\n39: - What Failed\n40: - Exhausted Approaches\n41: - Ruled-Out Directions\n42: - Next Focus\n43: \n44: Update protocol:\n45: \n46: - read strategy before each iteration;\n47: - choose one focus from `Next Focus`;\n48: - append what worked, failed, and was ruled out;\n49: - update answered/open questions through reducer-owned sections;\n50: - when a STOP candidate is blocked, override `Next Focus` with the blocker recovery focus.\n51: \n52: ---\n53: \n54: ## 3. ITERATION FILES\n55: \n56: Iteration files are write-once markdown narratives.\n57: \n58: ```text\n59: research/iterations/iteration-001.md\n60: research/iterations/iteration-002.md\n61: research/iterations/iteration-003.md\n62: ```\n63: \n64: Required shape:\n65: \n66: | Markdown Element | Required Content |\n67: |------------------|------------------|\n68: | H1 title | `Iteration N: Focus Area` |\n69: | `Focus` section | What this iteration investigated |\n70: | `Findings` section | Evidence-backed findings with source citations |\n71: | `Sources Consulted` section | Files, URLs, memory hits, or commands used |\n72: | `Assessment` section | `newInfoRatio`, novelty justification, and confidence notes |\n73: | `Reflection` section | What worked, failed, or was ruled out |\n74: | `Recommended Next Focus` section | One concrete next focus |\n75: \n76: Every finding must cite a source such as `[SOURCE: file:path:line]` or `[SOURCE: https://example.test]`.\n77: \n78: ---\n79: \n80: ## 4. RESEARCH SYNTHESIS\n81: \n82: `research.md` is the workflow-owned synthesis output at `{artifact_dir}/research.md`.\n83: \n84: Rules:\n85: \n86: - progressive synthesis may update the file during the loop;\n87: - final synthesis consolidates duplicate findings and unresolved gaps;\n88: - prior findings are not silently overwritten;\n89: - generated or machine-owned sections must be marked explicitly when the workflow uses them;\n90: - when `resource_map_present` is true, cite `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` in References.\n91: \n92: ---\n93: \n94: ## 5. DASHBOARD\n95: \n96: `deep-research-dashboard.md` is auto-generated from JSONL, strategy, and registry state.\n97: \n98: Expected sections:\n99: \n100: | Section | Source |\n101: |---------|--------|\n102: | Iteration Table | JSONL iteration records |\n103: | Question Status | Strategy + registry |\n104: | Convergence Trend | `convergenceSignals` + reducer |\n105: | Dead Ends | JSONL `ruledOut` + strategy |\n106: | Blocked Stops | Registry blocked-stop history |\n107: | Graph Convergence | Graph convergence registry fields |\n108: | Next Focus | Strategy |\n109: \n110: Generation rules:\n111: \n112: - regenerate after each iteration evaluation;\n113: - compute derived values from raw state;\n114: - overwrite the full dashboard rather than appending;\n115: - if state is missing, write a minimal \"No iteration data available\" dashboard;\n116: - agent writes are discarded on next refresh.\n117: \n118: ---\n119: \n120: ## 6. RESOURCE MAP\n121: \n122: When `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` exists at init:\n123: \n124: - persist `resource_map_present: true` in config;\n125: - summarize section counts and themes into strategy `Known Context`;\n126: - treat listed files as known inventory, not net-new discoveries;\n127: - cite the map in final synthesis references;\n128: - emit `{artifact_dir}/resource-map.md` from converged deltas unless disabled.\n129: \n130: When absent:\n131: \n132: - persist `resource_map_present: false`;\n133: - write `resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate` into `Known Context`;\n134: - continue normally.\n135: \n136: ---\n137: \n138: ## 7. SPEC ANCHORING OUTPUT\n139: \n140: `references/protocol/spec_check_protocol.md` defines bounded `spec.md` writes:\n141: \n142: - acquire `research/.deep-research.lock`;\n143: - classify `folder_state`;\n144: - seed or append bounded context during init when allowed;\n145: - replace exactly one generated findings fence during synthesis.\n146: \n147: This output path is protocol-owned, not iteration-agent owned.\n\n(End of file - total 147 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Research Output Files Reference\ndescription: Markdown output structures for strategy, iterations, dashboard, synthesis, and resource-map artifacts.\n---\n\n# Deep Research Output Files Reference\n\nThis reference covers human-readable packet outputs. JSONL records live in `state_jsonl.md`; reducer ownership lives in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefine the human-readable deep-research packet outputs: strategy, iteration markdown, synthesis, dashboard, resource map, and bounded spec anchoring.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this reference when writing or validating markdown outputs rather than JSONL records.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_outputs.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Research Output Files Reference\ndescription: Markdown output structures for strategy, iterations, dashboard, synthesis, and resource-map artifacts.\n---\n\n# Deep Research Output Files Reference\n\nThis reference covers human-readable packet outputs. JSONL records live in `state_jsonl.md`; reducer ownership lives in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefine the human-readable deep-research packet outputs: strategy, iteration markdown, synthesis, dashboard, resource map, and bounded spec anchoring.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this reference when writing or validating markdown outputs rather than JSONL records.\n\n### Core Principle\n\nHuman-readable outputs must stay synchronized with raw state and respect reducer ownership.\n\n---\n\n## 2. STRATEGY FILE\n\n`deep-research-strategy.md` is the persistent research plan. The reducer owns machine-managed sections.\n\nRequired sections:\n\n- Research Topic\n- Known Context\n- Key Questions\n- Answered Questions\n- What Worked\n- What Failed\n- Exhausted Approaches\n- Ruled-Out Directions\n- Next Focus\n\nUpdate protocol:\n\n- read strategy before each iteration;\n- choose one focus from `Next Focus`;\n- append what worked, failed, and was ruled out;\n- update answered/open questions through reducer-owned sections;\n- when a STOP candidate is blocked, override `Next Focus` with the blocker recovery focus.\n\n---\n\n## 3. ITERATION FILES\n\nIteration files are write-once markdown narratives.\n\n```text\nresearch/iterations/iteration-001.md\nresearch/iterations/iteration-002.md\nresearch/iterations/iteration-003.md\n```\n\nRequired shape:\n\n| Markdown Element | Required Content |\n|------------------|------------------|\n| H1 title | `Iteration N: Focus Area` |\n| `Focus` section | What this iteration investigated |\n| `Findings` section | Evidence-backed findings with source citations |\n| `Sources Consulted` section | Files, URLs, memory hits, or commands used |\n| `Assessment` section | `newInfoRatio`, novelty justification, and confidence notes |\n| `Reflection` section | What worked, failed, or was ruled out |\n| `Recommended Next Focus` section | One concrete next focus |\n\nEvery finding must cite a source such as `[SOURCE: file:path:line]` or `[SOURCE: https://example.test]`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RESEARCH SYNTHESIS\n\n`research.md` is the workflow-owned synthesis output at `{artifact_dir}/research.md`.\n\nRules:\n\n- progressive synthesis may update the file during the loop;\n- final synthesis consolidates duplicate findings and unresolved gaps;\n- prior findings are not silently overwritten;\n- generated or machine-owned sections must be marked explicitly when the workflow uses them;\n- when `resource_map_present` is true, cite `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` in References.\n\n---\n\n## 5. DASHBOARD\n\n`deep-research-dashboard.md` is auto-generated from JSONL, strategy, and registry state.\n\nExpected sections:\n\n| Section | Source |\n|---------|--------|\n| Iteration Table | JSONL iteration records |\n| Question Status | Strategy + registry |\n| Convergence Trend | `convergenceSignals` + reducer |\n| Dead Ends | JSONL `ruledOut` + strategy |\n| Blocked Stops | Registry blocked-stop history |\n| Graph Convergence | Graph convergence registry fields |\n| Next Focus | Strategy |\n\nGeneration rules:\n\n- regenerate after each iteration evaluation;\n- compute derived values from raw state;\n- overwrite the full dashboard rather than appending;\n- if state is missing, write a minimal \"No iteration data available\" dashboard;\n- agent writes are discarded on next refresh.\n\n---\n\n## 6. RESOURCE MAP\n\nWhen `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` exists at init:\n\n- persist `resource_map_present: true` in config;\n- summarize section counts and themes into strategy `Known Context`;\n- treat listed files as known inventory, not net-new discoveries;\n- cite the map in final synthesis references;\n- emit `{artifact_dir}/resource-map.md` from converged deltas unless disabled.\n\nWhen absent:\n\n- persist `resource_map_present: false`;\n- write `resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate` into `Known Context`;\n- continue normally.\n\n---\n\n## 7. SPEC ANCHORING OUTPUT\n\n`references/protocol/spec_check_protocol.md` defines bounded `spec.md` writes:\n\n- acquire `research/.deep-research.lock`;\n- classify `folder_state`;\n- seed or append bounded context during init when allowed;\n- replace exactly one generated findings fence during synthesis.\n\nThis output path is protocol-owned, not iteration-agent owned.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":147,"totalLines":147,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-research/references/state/state_outputs.md","time":{"start":1780736003939,"end":1780736003945}},"id":"prt_e9c230f54001ZR1BvAo537x3Us","sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","messageID":"msg_e9c22f4e7001AVFbL8QlqZeuBd"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780736004228,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"id":"prt_e9c231081001Zdg7j9AdqnbL2d","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"3afaecc5f0f80d2677ff70d344c805c13182b346","messageID":"msg_e9c22f4e7001AVFbL8QlqZeuBd","sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":63451,"input":63285,"output":166,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":0}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780736010131,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"id":"prt_e9c2327910017e6WeSVyarcq7D","messageID":"msg_e9c2311a6001D5d2vdgoNAde3u","sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","snapshot":"3afaecc5f0f80d2677ff70d344c805c13182b346","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780736012303,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_p5n45fa4skd1_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_signals.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_signals.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Convergence Signals Reference\n3: description: Signal definitions, scoring rules, and reports for deep-research convergence.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Convergence Signals Reference\n7: \n8: This reference defines the live deep-research convergence signals. The compact stop contract lives in `convergence.md`.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### Purpose\n15: \n16: Define the live convergence signals, scoring rules, threshold semantics, and reporting shape used by deep-research loops.\n17: \n18: ### When to Use\n19: \n20: Load this reference when calculating `newInfoRatio`, explaining a composite STOP vote, debugging stuck counts, or validating convergence dashboards.\n21: \n22: ### Core Principle\n23: \n24: Signals nominate STOP; legal-stop and graph gates authorize or block it.\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## 2. SIGNAL MODEL\n29: \n30: The live model uses three weighted signals and normalizes by the weight of the signals that have enough data to run.\n31: \n32: | Signal | Weight | Requires | STOP Vote |\n33: |--------|--------|----------|-----------|\n34: | Rolling Average | `0.30` | 3 evidence iterations | Average of last 3 `newInfoRatio` values is below `convergenceThreshold` |\n35: | MAD Noise Floor | `0.35` | 4 evidence iterations | Latest `newInfoRatio` is at or below `MAD * 1.4826` |\n36: | Question Entropy | `0.35` | At least 1 key question | Evidence-backed coverage is at least `0.85` |\n37: \n38: `thought` iterations are excluded from rolling average, MAD, and stuck counting because they are analytical-only. `insight` iterations are included in convergence signals but do not count as stuck.\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## 3. NEW INFO RATIO\n43: \n44: `newInfoRatio` measures how much an iteration added relative to accumulated research knowledge.\n45: \n46: | Ratio | Meaning |\n47: |-------|---------|\n48: | `1.0` | Mostly new findings or first broad pass |\n49: | `0.7` | Several new findings plus some refinements |\n50: | `0.5` | Mixed new and repeated material |\n51: | `0.2` | Mostly confirmation or marginal novelty |\n52: | `0.0` | No new information |\n53: \n54: Agent assessment guidance:\n55: \n56: - Fully new finding: count as `1.0`.\n57: - Refinement of known finding: count as partial novelty.\n58: - Ruled-out direction: count as valuable negative knowledge when it removes a plausible path.\n59: - Tentative single-source finding: contribute less than verified or multi-source evidence.\n60: - Simplicity bonus may add up to `0.10`, capped at `1.0`, when an iteration materially reduces the search space.\n61: \n62: Every iteration record should include `newInfoRatio` and `noveltyJustification`; see `../state/state_jsonl.md`.\n63: \n64: ---\n65: \n66: ## 4. STUCK COUNT\n67: \n68: `stuckCount` is consecutive no-progress evidence iterations.\n69: \n70: ```text\n71: for each iteration from newest to oldest:\n72:   skip status == \"thought\"\n73:   stop counting when status == \"insight\"\n74:   count if status == \"stuck\" or newInfoRatio <= noProgressThreshold\n75:   stop counting on any productive evidence iteration\n76: ```\n77: \n78: Default threshold behavior:\n79: \n80: - `stuckThreshold`: `3`\n81: - `noProgressThreshold`: implementation default aligned with the workflow's recovery check\n82: - Recovery route: `convergence_recovery.md`\n83: \n84: ---\n85: \n86: ## 5. ROLLING AVERAGE\n87: \n88: Rolling average uses the last three evidence iterations.\n89: \n90: ```text\n91: evidenceIterations = iterations where status != \"thought\"\n92: recent = last 3 evidenceIterations\n93: rollingAvg = mean(recent.newInfoRatio)\n94: rollingStop = rollingAvg < convergenceThreshold\n95: ```\n96: \n97: This signal is unavailable before three evidence iterations. The composite vote normalizes over active signals, so early runs can still use question coverage without pretending the rolling signal exists.\n98: \n99: ---\n100: \n101: ## 6. MAD NOISE FLOOR\n102: \n103: MAD compares the latest ratio against the noise floor in the accumulated evidence ratios.\n104: \n105: ```text\n106: ratios = evidenceIterations.newInfoRatio\n107: medianRatio = median(ratios)\n108: mad = median(abs(ratio - medianRatio) for ratio in ratios)\n109: noiseFloor = mad * 1.4826\n110: madStop = latestEvidenceRatio <= noiseFloor\n111: ```\n112: \n113: Interpretation:\n114: \n115: | Condition | Meaning |\n116: |-----------|---------|\n117: | Latest ratio above floor | Signal still exceeds observed noise |\n118: | Latest ratio within floor | New findings may be indistinguishable from noise |\n119: | Very high floor | Iteration quality is unstable; narrow the focus before trusting STOP |\n120: \n121: ---\n122: \n123: ## 7. QUESTION ENTROPY\n124: \n125: Question entropy is evidence-backed key-question coverage.\n126: \n127: ```text\n128: answered = count(keyQuestions with evidence-backed answers)\n129: total = count(keyQuestions)\n130: coverage = answered / total\n131: entropyStop = coverage >= 0.85\n132: ```\n133: \n134: Tentative-only findings do not satisfy evidence-backed coverage. Graph events may add extra STOP blockers when graph coverage disagrees with inline question coverage; see `convergence_graph.md`.\n135: \n136: ---\n137: \n138: ## 8. COMPOSITE SCORE\n139: \n140: ```text\n141: activeSignals = signals with enough data\n142: stopScore = sum(signal.weight for active STOP votes) / sum(active signal weights)\n143: stopCandidate = stopScore > 0.60\n144: ```\n145: \n146: The score nominates STOP only. `convergence.md` defines the legal-stop gates that decide whether the loop may exit.\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ## 9. REPORTING\n151: \n152: Every completed loop should report:\n153: \n154: ```text\n155: CONVERGENCE REPORT\n156: ------------------\n157: Stop reason: converged | maxIterationsReached | userPaused | stuckRecovery | error\n158: Iterations completed: N\n159: Questions answered: X/Y\n160: Average newInfoRatio trend: [...]\n161: Composite stop score: 0.XX\n162: Signals:\n163:   Rolling Avg (w=0.30): STOP|CONTINUE\n164:   MAD Noise (w=0.35): STOP|CONTINUE\n165:   Entropy (w=0.35): STOP|CONTINUE\n166: Legal-stop gates: pass|blocked\n167: Graph gates: pass|blocked|not_applicable\n168: ```\n169: \n170: Dashboard and registry fields derived from these signals are documented in `../state/state_reducer_registry.md`.\n171: \n172: ---\n173: \n174: ## 10. THRESHOLD TUNING\n175: \n176: | Goal | Adjustment |\n177: |------|------------|\n178: | Deeper research | Lower `convergenceThreshold`, raise `maxIterations` |\n179: | Faster completion | Raise `convergenceThreshold`, lower `maxIterations` |\n180: | More stuck recovery | Lower `stuckThreshold` cautiously |\n181: | Fewer false stops | Keep legal-stop and graph gates enabled |\n182: \n183: Optimizer-managed fields are described in `convergence_reference_only.md`. Optimizer proposals are advisory and do not override locked stop-contract fields.\n\n(End of file - total 183 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Convergence Signals Reference\ndescription: Signal definitions, scoring rules, and reports for deep-research convergence.\n---\n\n# Convergence Signals Reference\n\nThis reference defines the live deep-research convergence signals. The compact stop contract lives in `convergence.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefine the live convergence signals, scoring rules, threshold semantics, and reporting shape used by deep-research loops.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this reference when calculating `newInfoRatio`, explaining a composite STOP vote, debugging stuck counts, or validating convergence dashboards.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_signals.md","text":"---\ntitle: Convergence Signals Reference\ndescription: Signal definitions, scoring rules, and reports for deep-research convergence.\n---\n\n# Convergence Signals Reference\n\nThis reference defines the live deep-research convergence signals. The compact stop contract lives in `convergence.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefine the live convergence signals, scoring rules, threshold semantics, and reporting shape used by deep-research loops.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this reference when calculating `newInfoRatio`, explaining a composite STOP vote, debugging stuck counts, or validating convergence dashboards.\n\n### Core Principle\n\nSignals nominate STOP; legal-stop and graph gates authorize or block it.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SIGNAL MODEL\n\nThe live model uses three weighted signals and normalizes by the weight of the signals that have enough data to run.\n\n| Signal | Weight | Requires | STOP Vote |\n|--------|--------|----------|-----------|\n| Rolling Average | `0.30` | 3 evidence iterations | Average of last 3 `newInfoRatio` values is below `convergenceThreshold` |\n| MAD Noise Floor | `0.35` | 4 evidence iterations | Latest `newInfoRatio` is at or below `MAD * 1.4826` |\n| Question Entropy | `0.35` | At least 1 key question | Evidence-backed coverage is at least `0.85` |\n\n`thought` iterations are excluded from rolling average, MAD, and stuck counting because they are analytical-only. `insight` iterations are included in convergence signals but do not count as stuck.\n\n---\n\n## 3. NEW INFO RATIO\n\n`newInfoRatio` measures how much an iteration added relative to accumulated research knowledge.\n\n| Ratio | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| `1.0` | Mostly new findings or first broad pass |\n| `0.7` | Several new findings plus some refinements |\n| `0.5` | Mixed new and repeated material |\n| `0.2` | Mostly confirmation or marginal novelty |\n| `0.0` | No new information |\n\nAgent assessment guidance:\n\n- Fully new finding: count as `1.0`.\n- Refinement of known finding: count as partial novelty.\n- Ruled-out direction: count as valuable negative knowledge when it removes a plausible path.\n- Tentative single-source finding: contribute less than verified or multi-source evidence.\n- Simplicity bonus may add up to `0.10`, capped at `1.0`, when an iteration materially reduces the search space.\n\nEvery iteration record should include `newInfoRatio` and `noveltyJustification`; see `../state/state_jsonl.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. STUCK COUNT\n\n`stuckCount` is consecutive no-progress evidence iterations.\n\n```text\nfor each iteration from newest to oldest:\n  skip status == \"thought\"\n  stop counting when status == \"insight\"\n  count if status == \"stuck\" or newInfoRatio <= noProgressThreshold\n  stop counting on any productive evidence iteration\n```\n\nDefault threshold behavior:\n\n- `stuckThreshold`: `3`\n- `noProgressThreshold`: implementation default aligned with the workflow's recovery check\n- Recovery route: `convergence_recovery.md`\n\n---\n\n## 5. ROLLING AVERAGE\n\nRolling average uses the last three evidence iterations.\n\n```text\nevidenceIterations = iterations where status != \"thought\"\nrecent = last 3 evidenceIterations\nrollingAvg = mean(recent.newInfoRatio)\nrollingStop = rollingAvg < convergenceThreshold\n```\n\nThis signal is unavailable before three evidence iterations. The composite vote normalizes over active signals, so early runs can still use question coverage without pretending the rolling signal exists.\n\n---\n\n## 6. MAD NOISE FLOOR\n\nMAD compares the latest ratio against the noise floor in the accumulated evidence ratios.\n\n```text\nratios = evidenceIterations.newInfoRatio\nmedianRatio = median(ratios)\nmad = median(abs(ratio - medianRatio) for ratio in ratios)\nnoiseFloor = mad * 1.4826\nmadStop = latestEvidenceRatio <= noiseFloor\n```\n\nInterpretation:\n\n| Condition | Meaning |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Latest ratio above floor | Signal still exceeds observed noise |\n| Latest ratio within floor | New findings may be indistinguishable from noise |\n| Very high floor | Iteration quality is unstable; narrow the focus before trusting STOP |\n\n---\n\n## 7. QUESTION ENTROPY\n\nQuestion entropy is evidence-backed key-question coverage.\n\n```text\nanswered = count(keyQuestions with evidence-backed answers)\ntotal = count(keyQuestions)\ncoverage = answered / total\nentropyStop = coverage >= 0.85\n```\n\nTentative-only findings do not satisfy evidence-backed coverage. Graph events may add extra STOP blockers when graph coverage disagrees with inline question coverage; see `convergence_graph.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. COMPOSITE SCORE\n\n```text\nactiveSignals = signals with enough data\nstopScore = sum(signal.weight for active STOP votes) / sum(active signal weights)\nstopCandidate = stopScore > 0.60\n```\n\nThe score nominates STOP only. `convergence.md` defines the legal-stop gates that decide whether the loop may exit.\n\n---\n\n## 9. REPORTING\n\nEvery completed loop should report:\n\n```text\nCONVERGENCE REPORT\n------------------\nStop reason: converged | maxIterationsReached | userPaused | stuckRecovery | error\nIterations completed: N\nQuestions answered: X/Y\nAverage newInfoRatio trend: [...]\nComposite stop score: 0.XX\nSignals:\n  Rolling Avg (w=0.30): STOP|CONTINUE\n  MAD Noise (w=0.35): STOP|CONTINUE\n  Entropy (w=0.35): STOP|CONTINUE\nLegal-stop gates: pass|blocked\nGraph gates: pass|blocked|not_applicable\n```\n\nDashboard and registry fields derived from these signals are documented in `../state/state_reducer_registry.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 10. THRESHOLD TUNING\n\n| Goal | Adjustment |\n|------|------------|\n| Deeper research | Lower `convergenceThreshold`, raise `maxIterations` |\n| Faster completion | Raise `convergenceThreshold`, lower `maxIterations` |\n| More stuck recovery | Lower `stuckThreshold` cautiously |\n| Fewer false stops | Keep legal-stop and graph gates enabled |\n\nOptimizer-managed fields are described in `convergence_reference_only.md`. Optimizer proposals are advisory and do not override locked stop-contract fields.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":183,"totalLines":183,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_signals.md","time":{"start":1780736012295,"end":1780736012302}},"id":"prt_e9c232c1600111uaJkKu31x6CG","sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","messageID":"msg_e9c2311a6001D5d2vdgoNAde3u"}}
