{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780736372129,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"edit","callID":"call_function_4fgiocqdqb6i_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md","oldString":"## 5. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n\n(none yet)\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n\n## 6. WHAT WORKED\n\n- (populated after iteration 1)\n\n## 7. WHAT FAILED\n\n- (populated after iteration 1)\n\n## 8. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n\n(none yet)\n\n## 9. RULED-OUT DIRECTIONS\n\n(none yet)\n\n## 10. NEXT FOCUS\n\nStart with **KQ1** (37-tool parity matrix) — it anchors every other question; pair it with a quick KQ2 scan to surface daemon-bound affordances.","newString":"## 5. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n\n- KQ1 — 37-tool parity matrix: 5 tools already ported (generate-context, cli.ts stats/bulk-delete, reindex-embeddings, validate-memory-quality); 32 are 1:1 handler ports with a CLI argv layer. 0 truly lost in the handler sense (KQ3 may surface protocol-affordance losses).\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n\n## 6. WHAT WORKED\n\n- Reading `TOOL_NAMES` sets as the source of truth (instead of guessing from a doc) is fast and produces a verifiable 37-row matrix (iteration 1).\n\n## 7. WHAT FAILED\n\n- (none this iteration)\n\n## 8. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n\n- (none yet)\n\n## 9. RULED-OUT DIRECTIONS\n\n- \"11 CLIs\" framing as broad parity evidence — 10/11 are operational utilities, not user-facing tool substitutes (iteration 1, finding 1.9).\n- Treating KQ1 parity matrix as a sufficient zero-loss verdict — KQ3 protocol affordances must also be evaluated (iteration 1, finding 1.8).\n\n## 10. NEXT FOCUS\n\nKQ2 — daemon-dependency audit. Classify each of the 37 tools as `daemon-free / daemon-helpful / daemon-required`; map the daemon-resident services to specific tools; produce the per-architecture (a/b/c) loss table."},"output":"Edit applied successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"diff":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -28,31 +28,32 @@\n - Legal early stop only via all-questions-answered.\n \n ## 5. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n \n-(none yet)\n+- KQ1 — 37-tool parity matrix: 5 tools already ported (generate-context, cli.ts stats/bulk-delete, reindex-embeddings, validate-memory-quality); 32 are 1:1 handler ports with a CLI argv layer. 0 truly lost in the handler sense (KQ3 may surface protocol-affordance losses).\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n \n ## 6. WHAT WORKED\n \n-- (populated after iteration 1)\n+- Reading `TOOL_NAMES` sets as the source of truth (instead of guessing from a doc) is fast and produces a verifiable 37-row matrix (iteration 1).\n \n ## 7. WHAT FAILED\n \n-- (populated after iteration 1)\n+- (none this iteration)\n \n ## 8. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n \n-(none yet)\n+- (none yet)\n \n ## 9. RULED-OUT DIRECTIONS\n \n-(none yet)\n+- \"11 CLIs\" framing as broad parity evidence — 10/11 are operational utilities, not user-facing tool substitutes (iteration 1, finding 1.9).\n+- Treating KQ1 parity matrix as a sufficient zero-loss verdict — KQ3 protocol affordances must also be evaluated (iteration 1, finding 1.8).\n \n ## 10. NEXT FOCUS\n \n-Start with **KQ1** (37-tool parity matrix) — it anchors every other question; pair it with a quick KQ2 scan to surface daemon-bound affordances.\n+KQ2 — daemon-dependency audit. Classify each of the 37 tools as `daemon-free / daemon-helpful / daemon-required`; map the daemon-resident services to specific tools; produce the per-architecture (a/b/c) loss table.\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n \n ## 11. KNOWN CONTEXT (analyst-owned)\n","filediff":{"file":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -28,31 +28,32 @@\n - Legal early stop only via all-questions-answered.\n \n ## 5. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n \n-(none yet)\n+- KQ1 — 37-tool parity matrix: 5 tools already ported (generate-context, cli.ts stats/bulk-delete, reindex-embeddings, validate-memory-quality); 32 are 1:1 handler ports with a CLI argv layer. 0 truly lost in the handler sense (KQ3 may surface protocol-affordance losses).\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n \n ## 6. WHAT WORKED\n \n-- (populated after iteration 1)\n+- Reading `TOOL_NAMES` sets as the source of truth (instead of guessing from a doc) is fast and produces a verifiable 37-row matrix (iteration 1).\n \n ## 7. WHAT FAILED\n \n-- (populated after iteration 1)\n+- (none this iteration)\n \n ## 8. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n \n-(none yet)\n+- (none yet)\n \n ## 9. RULED-OUT DIRECTIONS\n \n-(none yet)\n+- \"11 CLIs\" framing as broad parity evidence — 10/11 are operational utilities, not user-facing tool substitutes (iteration 1, finding 1.9).\n+- Treating KQ1 parity matrix as a sufficient zero-loss verdict — KQ3 protocol affordances must also be evaluated (iteration 1, finding 1.8).\n \n ## 10. NEXT FOCUS\n \n-Start with **KQ1** (37-tool parity matrix) — it anchors every other question; pair it with a quick KQ2 scan to surface daemon-bound affordances.\n+KQ2 — daemon-dependency audit. Classify each of the 37 tools as `daemon-free / daemon-helpful / daemon-required`; map the daemon-resident services to specific tools; produce the per-architecture (a/b/c) loss table.\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n \n ## 11. KNOWN CONTEXT (analyst-owned)\n","additions":7,"deletions":6},"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1780736372123,"end":1780736372127}},"id":"prt_e9c288b8c001KQK72xYbzQdV6x","sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","messageID":"msg_e9c287271001UCCAAatXCiDNS4"}}
