{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780736856967,"sessionID":"ses_163de1863ffeLd3K58IkmWaFwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"edit","callID":"call_function_r7lba9gb0we7_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md","oldString":"## 5. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n\n- KQ1 — 37-tool parity matrix: 5 tools already ported (generate-context, cli.ts stats/bulk-delete, reindex-embeddings, validate-memory-quality); 32 are 1:1 handler ports with a CLI argv layer. 0 truly lost in the handler sense (KQ3 may surface protocol-affordance losses).\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n\n## 6. WHAT WORKED\n\n- Reading `TOOL_NAMES` sets as the source of truth (instead of guessing from a doc) is fast and produces a verifiable 37-row matrix (iteration 1).\n\n## 7. WHAT FAILED\n\n- (none this iteration)\n\n## 8. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n\n- (none yet)\n\n## 9. RULED-OUT DIRECTIONS\n\n- \"11 CLIs\" framing as broad parity evidence — 10/11 are operational utilities, not user-facing tool substitutes (iteration 1, finding 1.9).\n- Treating KQ1 parity matrix as a sufficient zero-loss verdict — KQ3 protocol affordances must also be evaluated (iteration 1, finding 1.8).\n\n## 10. NEXT FOCUS\n\nKQ2 — daemon-dependency audit. Classify each of the 37 tools as `daemon-free / daemon-helpful / daemon-required`; map the daemon-resident services to specific tools; produce the per-architecture (a/b/c) loss table.","newString":"## 5. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n\n- KQ1 — 37-tool parity matrix: 5 tools already ported (generate-context, cli.ts stats/bulk-delete, reindex-embeddings, validate-memory-quality); 32 are 1:1 handler ports with a CLI argv layer. 0 truly lost in the handler sense.\n- KQ2 — daemon-dependency audit: 6 services catalogued (S1..S6); 24/37 tools are daemon-free, 13/37 are soft-dependent, 0 are hard-required. Per-architecture loss table: (a) loses 3 services (S1, S2, S4); (b) keeps all 6; (c) keeps all 6 + auto-spawn.\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n\n## 6. WHAT WORKED\n\n- Reading `TOOL_NAMES` sets as the source of truth is fast and produces a verifiable 37-row matrix (iteration 1).\n- Tracing `startFileWatcher` and its only call site in `dist/context-server.js:1740` is the cleanest way to determine daemon-only services (iteration 2).\n- Reading `spec-folder-mutex.ts:14-86` and `working-memory.ts:171-623` to verify \"interprocess\" / \"per-session\" claims (iteration 2).\n\n## 7. WHAT FAILED\n\n- (none this iteration)\n\n## 8. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n\n- (none yet)\n\n## 9. RULED-OUT DIRECTIONS\n\n- \"11 CLIs\" framing as broad parity evidence (iteration 1, finding 1.9).\n- Treating KQ1 parity matrix as a sufficient zero-loss verdict (iteration 1, finding 1.8).\n- \"Single-writer = daemon-resident\" claim — interprocess by design (iteration 2, ruled-out block).\n- \"Warm session briefs = daemon hot-cache\" claim — per-session SQLite rows, not in-memory daemon cache (iteration 2, finding 2.8).\n\n## 10. NEXT FOCUS\n\nKQ3 — MCP-only affordances and concrete CLI replacements. Three \"LOST\" rows in the per-architecture loss table need replacement designs: tool-schema auto-discovery, per-tool runtime permissioning, `-32001` retryable semantics. The session-proxy replay classification is already covered (kept in b/c; CLI implements its own retry in a)."},"output":"Edit applied successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"diff":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -28,15 +28,18 @@\n - Legal early stop only via all-questions-answered.\n \n ## 5. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n \n-- KQ1 — 37-tool parity matrix: 5 tools already ported (generate-context, cli.ts stats/bulk-delete, reindex-embeddings, validate-memory-quality); 32 are 1:1 handler ports with a CLI argv layer. 0 truly lost in the handler sense (KQ3 may surface protocol-affordance losses).\n+- KQ1 — 37-tool parity matrix: 5 tools already ported (generate-context, cli.ts stats/bulk-delete, reindex-embeddings, validate-memory-quality); 32 are 1:1 handler ports with a CLI argv layer. 0 truly lost in the handler sense.\n+- KQ2 — daemon-dependency audit: 6 services catalogued (S1..S6); 24/37 tools are daemon-free, 13/37 are soft-dependent, 0 are hard-required. Per-architecture loss table: (a) loses 3 services (S1, S2, S4); (b) keeps all 6; (c) keeps all 6 + auto-spawn.\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n \n ## 6. WHAT WORKED\n \n-- Reading `TOOL_NAMES` sets as the source of truth (instead of guessing from a doc) is fast and produces a verifiable 37-row matrix (iteration 1).\n+- Reading `TOOL_NAMES` sets as the source of truth is fast and produces a verifiable 37-row matrix (iteration 1).\n+- Tracing `startFileWatcher` and its only call site in `dist/context-server.js:1740` is the cleanest way to determine daemon-only services (iteration 2).\n+- Reading `spec-folder-mutex.ts:14-86` and `working-memory.ts:171-623` to verify \"interprocess\" / \"per-session\" claims (iteration 2).\n \n ## 7. WHAT FAILED\n \n - (none this iteration)\n@@ -46,14 +49,16 @@\n - (none yet)\n \n ## 9. RULED-OUT DIRECTIONS\n \n-- \"11 CLIs\" framing as broad parity evidence — 10/11 are operational utilities, not user-facing tool substitutes (iteration 1, finding 1.9).\n-- Treating KQ1 parity matrix as a sufficient zero-loss verdict — KQ3 protocol affordances must also be evaluated (iteration 1, finding 1.8).\n+- \"11 CLIs\" framing as broad parity evidence (iteration 1, finding 1.9).\n+- Treating KQ1 parity matrix as a sufficient zero-loss verdict (iteration 1, finding 1.8).\n+- \"Single-writer = daemon-resident\" claim — interprocess by design (iteration 2, ruled-out block).\n+- \"Warm session briefs = daemon hot-cache\" claim — per-session SQLite rows, not in-memory daemon cache (iteration 2, finding 2.8).\n \n ## 10. NEXT FOCUS\n \n-KQ2 — daemon-dependency audit. Classify each of the 37 tools as `daemon-free / daemon-helpful / daemon-required`; map the daemon-resident services to specific tools; produce the per-architecture (a/b/c) loss table.\n+KQ3 — MCP-only affordances and concrete CLI replacements. Three \"LOST\" rows in the per-architecture loss table need replacement designs: tool-schema auto-discovery, per-tool runtime permissioning, `-32001` retryable semantics. The session-proxy replay classification is already covered (kept in b/c; CLI implements its own retry in a).\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n \n ## 11. KNOWN CONTEXT (analyst-owned)\n","filediff":{"file":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/lineages/minimax/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -28